<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Asimov: anything, read all his fiction prior to his departing this world; some of his nonfiction also a good read; Foundation ...........any and all that series; I,Robot.......and those.
<br />

<br />
Heinlein: read all of it; Stranger in a Strange Land (read it too many times); the Lazurus series including The Number of the Beast.
<br />

<br />
Herbert: his original Trilogy of Dune, the others beyond the Trilogy are ok; his other works are also good.
<br />

<br />
Piers Anthony: all the Xanthe series; some of his other fiction is good too
<br />

<br />
Pratchett: what fun reads , great to relax by.
<br />

<br />
Simmons: his Science fiction is good (Hyperion, etc.), his fiction takes getting into but is a good read.
<br />

<br />
Fiest: some good things early .
<br />

<br />
Nivens: the entire Ringworld series, and some of his other writing is good, including some of his collaboratives.
<br />

<br />
Goodkind: a very good up and coming author; fairly new but not = in last 10 years anyway - I am very far behind in his works.
<br />

<br />
For those enjoying Rice, take a look at Brian Lumley, if you haven't yet: the series on Vampyres is a marvelous twist on them and theirs - Necroscope is the first, all others listed on the pages by publishers are very good reads; Gods what I wouldn't give to have that series or the foundation story made into a movie - the effects these days would Roxxors.
<br />

<br />
Just to mention a few for your reading pleasure.............    <img src="images/smiles/icon_eek.gif" alt="icon_eek.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
